Singapore Stocks: Ezra, Golden Agri-Resources, Hong Leong Asia

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s
-- 
2011-08-16T09:29:47Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-16/hongkong-land-keppel-singapore-air-singapore-equity-preview.html
Singapore ’s Straits Times Index
dropped 1.5 percent to 2,832.73 at the close. About six stocks
fell for each that rose in the index of 30 companies.  The following shares were among the most active in the
market. Stock symbols are in parentheses after the company name.  Palm-oil producers: Crude palm-oil futures for October
delivery declined as much as 1.1 percent in  Kuala Lumpur  today,
heading for its first drop in five days.  Golden Agri-Resources
Ltd. (GGR)  , the world’s second-biggest palm-oil producer by
sales, lost 0.8 percent to 63.5 Singapore cents.  Indofood Agri
Resources Ltd. (IFAR)  , the plantation unit of  Indonesia ’s No.
1 noodle maker, sank 3.4 percent to S$1.265.  Wilmar
International Ltd. (WIL)  , the world’s biggest palm-oil
processor, dropped 2.1 percent to S$5.13.  Ezra Holdings Ltd. (EZRA)  , a provider of logistics
services to the oil and gas industry, surged 6.7 percent to 96
Singapore cents, the most since February 2010. The company said
its EMAS AMC unit won a contract to install wellhead platforms
and pipelines for Chevron Corp. in  Thailand . Financial details
weren’t disclosed. With this contract, EMAS AMC unit’s orderbook
has exceeded $600 million, Ezra said.  Hong Leong Asia Ltd. (HLA)  , a maker of freezers and air
conditioners that gets about 88 percent of sales from China,
dropped 1.7 percent to S$1.75. Credit Suisse Group AG cut its
rating to “neutral” from “outperform,” saying earnings in
the second half will be weaker amid tighter credit policies in
 China .  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jonathan Burgos in Singapore at 
